In the summer months, every year, it is a surprise which artists, are brought in by the organization of reggae lake festival. Customer Friendly. Partially wheelchair friendly with guidance. It is very busy.  Long queues for tickets, still goes smoothly, public restrooms available. Dogs on leash. Buses 41, 44, end stop metro 53. gaasperplas. From station Duivendrecht change to metro 54 direction CS and change at van der Made road to metro 53, direction gaasperplas final stop for this big reggae festival two days long.

Beautiful park with a large lake next door. There were some great cycle paths.

As you can see, when the weather is good, it's a great place to visit on a day out.

There's also a couple nice places where you can stop and take a break, sit down and have a picnic if you'd like.

I'd highly recommend to anyone who likes the outdoors. As an individual, couple, or even a family, it's a lovely place to visit - and even has some nice wildlife too!

name: Park de Oeverlanden
Translated_Review:
A bike path meanders on Parklands De Oeverlanden. The Anton Schleperspad.
Anton Schlepers, discoverer of Park De Oeverlanden, Amsterdam.

In 1981, he and partner Henk Gerritsen founded the association De Oeverlanden Blijven! to save the northern riparian lands of the Nieuwe Meer in Amsterdam from municipal building plans, which succeeded in 1985. Historic land in the context of the gay emancipation movement. From far away from the times when gays were still banished to garbage dumps beyond the Pesthuizen. Rather lost than rich! That dump was Parkland De Oeverlanden.

Recreationists now (not queer) are not reminded on Parklandschap De Oeverlanden that gays have turned the encroaching city here with activism on this spot beyond the Pesthuizen, on the dump De Oeverlanden.
Recreationists now (not queer), are eager to use this straight friendly enclave. By putting a fence around the gay cruise spot with Scottish Highlanders (and their flaxes), it was thought to achieve this. However the gay cruise spot has now gained its own bike paths in its enclave!
Anton Schlepers, the hero of Park the Oeverlanden, the gay, on the street signs there the discoverer. Euphemistically. Again the city advances, with plans for Park Landscape De Oeverlanden, at odds with the spirit of Anton Schlepers.

The little snack bar closed at five.  We had a good meal in the adjacent Popi & Haas restaurant - in the same building as Lalaland.  The beach is partly enclosed by fences, behind which bulldozers are still busy with sand, pipes and water.  Are we coming back?  Of course we will!

name: Strand Blijburg
Translated_Review:
Very cozy place when you enter it. A waiter soon arrives to take our order. A coffee and a beer ... couldn't be easier. After about 15 minutes. (We were sitting near the bar and we could see everything) our coffee and beer was finally made. The bar staff were standing around chatting, loafing and and walking shuffling through the establishment. There was a tray of beer and lemonade waiting for a waitress and she only came to get the tray after 10 minutes. There was pleasant chatter behind the bar and everyone looked at us and saw us not drinking anything.
Of course I know that on a hot day there isn't really a shot in the arm but I have worked in the hospitality industry and know that it can be veeeeeeeeeery more professional!!! It was a disappointment.

Great calisthenic park, close to the Sloterplaas lake.

It's a nice place to take a walk around the lake. Can take up to 1 hour for a complete round walk.

Spacious park, with green spots, old Amsterdam woods. Places that allow public barbecue. Clean up needed, if not cleaned up it can result in heavy fines.

Also a nice beach for a small amount people.
Check always for blauwe algen, it’s a bacteria in the water , which can cause big harm to dogs and human.
If you see warning signs, do not enter the water.

Boat rent available.

Shopping street west of the lake.

Hotels close to the lake as well available.

Easiest way to travel to the center is the tram.

Easy to reach by bus or streetcar from Centraal station, and a 35-minute walk from Sloterdijk station.

It is definitely worth a visit.

name: Sloterplas
Translated_Review:
A lake in which people can swim. Very nice in the summer! Near the roundabout between the streets Noordzijde and Oostoever there is a pier (wood and stone) where you can seat and soak your feet, sunbathe or jump into the lake (there are also stairs to go in the water). Dogs allowed (it's a public place), haven't seen dogs swimming, though; I guess because there is no easy way for them to go out of the water (there's no shore it's a pier). Only some occasional seaweed and very little waste in the water. Depending on the time there might not be any shadows to cover yourself from the sun! There is a point of drinking water near the roundabout!
You can also swim  in this lake or lie at Sloterpark.

If you are planning what to do this spring or summer, this is definitely the place you should visit.  Near the harbour there is a bar where you can  sit outside and look at the water and next to it there is also a corridor full of trees where it ends in a bay where you can also sit and contemplate the water. Really relaxing and beautiful to relax. :-). So dont tell me that you didn't know that this place exists. Grab your picnic basket and have fun.

name: Sloterplas
Translated_Review:
I really like this place at the weekend.
If you walk a little further (10 minutes) from streetcar 12 sloterpark into the park, you come to a quieter area.
Here you can lie right by the water, it's very quiet apart from the airplanes (which you can hear everywhere in Amsterdam) and you can be by yourself.
The water can be reached via a ladder and you can swim wonderfully!
It is also very clean and barbecuing is also possible.

If you're lucky, you'll hear the ice cream man and can refresh yourself when he passes by!

A clear recommendation for those seeking peace and quiet

name: Sloterplas Beach
Translated_Review:
Formerly known as Varkensbaai (translation: Bay of Pigs) this part of the Slotermeer has been spruced up a lot. Avoid actual swimming in the water during (late) summer months: the algea can cause deadly diseases at those times (keep an eye out for the signs that indicate wether the water is safe to enter).

A word of caution when visiting with (small) children: there are no lifeguards or first-aid volunteers. The Dutch have very stringenth rules about large public gatherings but not when they're government provided.

Had dr but nothing to say because who invents this has something of a twist. So it was sad.to well 2 hungry children.    Wel superfijn that at this beach free bands are given away by the municipality. There is much ge bbq what is not allowed here. Find it annoying if you are with your kids weggegrookt by such a thing. No control unfortunately. Also at the water is no control. Well you will think you have to watch out as a parent. Yet I see many little ones of 1.5 to 2 years wandering around alone because mom is too busy with friends ... but that's not my business.   Beach is just right. Quiet. No strange gear. Really a family beach.    Easy to reach and blue zone parking. Fine hear.   Would bring your own food and drinks. They don't have much in that little restaurant.

name: Sloterplas Beach

name: Kuuma Marineterrein
Translated_Review: Best public sauna in Amsterdam! Always nice to go in the morning and see the sunrise through the front window. The sauna is also located next to the water with a deck you can jump from. Perfect start of the day!

name: Kuuma Marineterrein
Translated_Review: Amsterdams best sauna! Kuuma sauna by the open water was a unique and invigorating experience. The cozy setup radiated warmth, and the option for open water swimming added a refreshing twist. A perfect blend of relaxation and exhilaration in a compact yet charming setting.

name: Kuuma Marineterrein
Translated_Review: I booked this wonderful place for a fun evening activity. Once we arrived, the code did not work, we called the assistance line (even though it was a weekend), they answered very quickly and we realized that we booked for the same day but am, not pm. We got a full refund, even though it was clearly our mistake. So nice, and the spot looks great! I can't wait to be back to actually use this place

name: Kuuma Marineterrein
Translated_Review: Discover Amsterdam's sauna magic! Dive into the water for the ultimate thrill. Enhance your experience and make unforgettable memories.

name: Kuuma Marineterrein
Translated_Review: Was worth every Euro. Ideal location for a sauna overlooking the water and city. Being able to take a shower or cold bucket of water balanced out the heat nicely. Would definitely go back

name: Kuuma Marineterrein
Translated_Review:
This sauna is now part of our Netherlands routine.
A must-do experience in Amsterdam for locals and tourists!
The location, view and privacy combined is amazing.

We were especially surprised by the ease of automatic access, available speaker, the auto-refill on the cold-shower tilt bucket and warm private dressing room space (which officially made this one of the best prepped sauna's we've ever been to.)

name: Kuuma Marineterrein
Translated_Review: Fantastic experience, high quality sauna.

name: Kuuma Marineterrein
Translated_Review: Wonderful! First a swim...and then just again

name: Kuuma Marineterrein
Translated_Review:
Nice view and concept!
Sauna front of canal.
Easy to book: online, choose a date, pay, then you will receive the code to enter (there is not reception it is just the sauna itself with a place to change clothes) the day before, you get there, you manage your time, you have a hourglass/timer inside do not stay longer than 15 minutes. Then get out. And go back in for another round. You will book the sauna for one hour. So do not be late because people booked for the hour after you. You can also go to the canal or have a shower outside.
Let it clean.
And enjoy your time

name: Kuuma Marineterrein
Translated_Review: All in all a nice sauna with a great view. It’s a bit disappointing that the shower didn’t work though and that they don’t mention in their website that there isn’t an inside shower to have a proper shower after sweating. Also make sure to bring enough water as there’s no tap, even though they mention in the website there is one.

name: Kuuma Marineterrein
Translated_Review:
This is such a cool initiative!

Little bespoke sauna perched on the edge of the Buitenzwembad Marineterrain overlooking the Scheepvartmuseum.

Simple and easy to use, ideal for a quick sauna session when you have the chance.

name: Kuuma Marineterrein
Translated_Review:
Amazing initiative and location. Overall great sauna, but some things could make it better ;-)

- there was no music/speaker possibility as advertised in the pictures
- there is no outside area to sit after the sauna use, especially when it rains, this would be nice

All in all we really liked it and hope to see more Kuuma Sauna's around Amsterdam

name: Kuuma Marineterrein
Translated_Review: Great experience. Non-negotiable benefit for your health and cardiovascular health. Bright and bubbly mood all day after. Swim in the cold water in the canal. Always meet new people. Amazing. I just wish it’d be an option of having something like a monthly pass or subscription if I’m going there very often during a week/month. As well I wish sometime to be alone in the sauna on my own, or to make available only for a couple, could be also an option. Maybe for earlier or later hours. Something like that. I’m sure it’d be a very popular option. Otherwise everything more that good for that price and experience

name: Kuuma Marineterrein

name: Youthland Outdoor Playground

Also good for parties.  Staff and visitors seem to care very deeply for the park, it is well cared for and well-used.  A great place for children to play, grow, and test themselves.  In back children have access to wood, hammer, and nails and can build fantastical forts or whatever.  Can't wait for ours to grow old enough to build!

name: Youthland Outdoor Playground
Translated_Review:
Give a group of young kids a bag of nails, a hammer and a saw, and wait for what could possibly go wrong...

Surprisingly not a whole lot. They can build cabins from pallet wood, or whatever else is available. Looks like fun!

Great playground for the smaller ones. Playing with or in the water. Playing with fire. Learning about growing food. A small petting zoo (Who knew deer love to eat chestnuts??) And inside tables, books and games.
Also a good place for children parties.

Sometimes the food/drink service is a bit slow, but relax! You are there to relax as well.

name: Youthland Outdoor Playground
Translated_Review: Youth Land is located on a small peninsula at the edge of Flevopark. To get there, you must first pass tennis club Tie-breakers. There are about 10 parking spots in front of the entrance to the tennis club and Jeugdland, which require payment at certain times. Jeugdland consists of a petting zoo, a clubhouse, a go-kart lab, a youth lab, a playground for smaller children and place where wooden huts are made. The grounds are large. In the clubhouse is after-school care and space that you can rent for a children's party, for example. You can also order coffee, tea and pastries here, among other things. The pastries are very tasty. Outside there is a terrace of picnic benches, among other things. Animals in the petting zoo include goats, a donkey, peacocks and rodents.

Terasmus the versatile kiosk where you can get everything, coffee, tea sandwiches, etc.

name: Erasmuspark
Translated_Review:
Erasmus Park is a fine park. Not very big. A lot of sports are played in it by groups of adults and children. And there are exercise machines there as well.

In the park there is a flower garden with long benches you can sit on. Further on is a playground with large sandbox, slide, house. Fun for the little ones. Adjacent is the 'Terrasmus' where you can have a snack (sandwich, toasted sandwich) or a drink. Both inside and outside you can sit. You can also take your coffee to the playground (handy!). Behind the eatery are toilets you can use.

Park is dog friendly. I think you can walk your dog in a large part of the park.

In the summer you can take a splash in the moat, next to the park. Ideal.

They have a good selection of craft beer. The unique terrace with repurposed items and the view of the canal on sunny hot days is the best.

name: De Ceuvel

We came for Lunch in Febuary, and the service was still excellent but the atmosphere a little quiet. We will be back again for a warm day in the summer, you could definitely spend an evening by the water with friends. The food was spot on and a nice break from all the meaty things we had been trying this holiday. The mustard soup was excellently balanced, with the mustard at the forefront without overpowering the rest of the elements of the dish. I was very excited to try this and it did not disappoint.

name: De Ceuvel
Translated_Review:
Special piece of Amsterdam. Atmospheric and alternative by the water in North. Rigged out of used materials and 2nd hand seating. Nice atmosphere. Service fine.

Beverage menu could really be better idd. Fine not to serve soft drinks, but make sure you have a wider range of fresh juices and good special beer (la Chouffe, Texels...). You only have gravy from packaging and I find that totally crooked again. In the end I ordered a blond beer and it turned out to be Gulpener. The only beer I really don't like.

-------

Dear owner, in response to your comment. You always react a bit prickly to feedback unfortunately. I give you 4 stars and also reported that your opportunity has huge potential. It's a cool place, with cool decor and atmosphere. Apparently you can't handle feedback very well. The specific story below...

When I asked for something like cassis on the terrace, I was informed that you don't have soda! That first of all. When I asked about beer, I was given a vague abstract of your apparently great offerings. There was a blonde beer so thought I'd take that.

Furthermore, half of your customers are sitting down to work and inside you hear (pretty loud but okay), 70's music in the case and hip-hop from the kitchen, mixed together. Are we allowed to think anything about that?

I would say, make a little clearer choices in what you want to be, make sure your staff knows the offerings well or make a nice drink menu and take feedback a little less prickly. Then you can see me back often in the future, at least when somewhat well-meaning critical guests are welcome.

name: De Ceuvel
Translated_Review:
To have a beer here you MUST provide your details to jamezz, your email address, phone number, name and bank details. You cannot order cash nor just with your debit card. I find this really super ridiculous for a beer, that you have to provide all this data, very bad. Just read the privacy statement of jamezz

Jamezz B.V. shares your personal data with various third parties if this is necessary for the
execution of the agreement and to comply with any legal obligation

- Sending our newsletter and/or advertising folder
- Calling or e-mailing you if this is necessary to carry out our services
- Inform you about changes in our services and products

So you pay for your beer and they take profit on your personal data on top of it.
I won't go there anymore, the flair is gone with such an invasive policy.

name: De Ceuvel
Translated_Review: The place has a fantastic ambiance. However the food was a bit disappointing and being an expensive restaurant made it even more disappinting.  The dishes were very interesting with unusual great ideas, some were really tasty, like ravioli with poppy seed, dill and hazelnut topping. But many of the flavors were really unbalanced. That ravioli had way too much balsamic vinegar and the filling was potato which in my opinion not great with pasta. And it was 17 euros. The pom pom dish (a deep fried musroom) could have been great bc of the unusual type of mushroom used, but it was way too oily. It was served with red cabbage which tasted more of cloves than cabbage. The sauce thoguh was really well made. And I also liked the chocolat pasta. One more thing: we got a hot apple juice with 30% alcohol which was merely hot and didnt taste like alcohol at all. Oh btw there were some issues with the ordering and some of our orders didnt get through although we payed.

name: De Ceuvel
Translated_Review:
Amazing Ambiance, that's a green house where we were seated with a sufficiently warming heater, there were blankets as well. :)
The place could've been in Spain or someother part of the world. I felt nostalgic for places I've not been to. :) If ever vegan restaurant was made to be this hip, we'd have less people eating meat I think. There are more than few example I can give that other restaurant can take from books of 'De Ceuvel'.

Example 1 : gracious selection of food, won't fall away from sensory pleasures you are used to. While still eating vegan food. Crispy pom pom blanc. Chocolate pasta.

Example 2 : Cocktail selection was magnificent, it was just intriguing to just try all of them. Apple sauce drink was amazing !

So why I still gave one star is because half of (Jemezz app) our order didn't make it to their system. Once they checked our bank transaction and accepted the order.
Next time I just gave up and threw the shrodingers cat philosophy for my drink . And the cat was indeed not in the box. :(

מקום מיוחד ממש
אקולוגי ברמה הכי גבוהה שראיתי. התפריט משתנה בהתאם לעונה, האוכל מושקע וטעים. גידול מקומי ובר קיימא. לקחנו את המרק עגבניות מעושנות, היינו ארבעה וכולנו עפנו באוויר והטעמים שיצאו מהמרק הזה נשארו בפה זמן רב.

האווירה סופר נעימה וגם השירות.
בנוסף יש מתחם סירות משרדים שלם ליד שחובה לעשות סיבוב
כל המתחם הוא למעשה פרויקט אקולוגי לשיקום האדמה והשמשה של המרחב לסירות (מבקום שישאר נטוש)
יש שלטים שמסבירים את הכל לאורך המסלול (הדק מעץ)
מומלץ

Luckily I didn’t cut my tongue nor swallow it - so that I know until now. After noticing it to the staff and showing the glass they simply replaced the bread for a new one and apologized saying it can happen - no, glass in your food cannot happen ! A bug, disgusting, but understandable. Someone’s hair, disgusting, but also understandable. But shattered glass ? Dangerous, sometimes deadly and overall just a massive mismanagement of kitchen accidents.

If you want to escape the tourist mass of the city center of Amsterdam, this is the place you should go to (and don’t forget your towel)!

Located in Amsterdam Noord, this amazing place offers a Café/restaurant, good music and a little lake or canal (I’m not quite sure) right next to De Ceuvel where you can dip in for a little swim!

The atmosphere is quite relaxed and therefore it is a good place to enjoy a sunny afternoon after a long day of sightseeing.

Another very positive aspect of De Ceuvel is that there are mainly locals (or at least it seems like that).

Definitely a nice spot to get an impression of the ‘non-touristic’ Amsterdam!

name: De Ceuvel
Translated_Review:
De Ceuvel is a restaurant on a mission: the menu carefully articulates there is a wider vision to deliver an eco-friendly and low environmental impact. There is a rough and ready feel; a reflection on the increasing trend towards sustainability and authenticity at the expense perhaps of luxury and, perhaps, the basic proposition.
So with very high praise and reviews, we came here for lunch.
Both the inside and outside decor give the feeling of an American style summer camp assembled by a shipwrecked crew with nothing to make shelter with other than washes ashore in the island with its mismatched tables and seating, home-made decorations and deliberately contrasting use of panel colour.
If a small group of dreadlocked hippies revealed themselves slouched onto patchwork beanbags wielding archaic musical instruments and lamenting the tax dodging and well-heeled patriarchy: I would have asked them where I could purchase the nearest fair trade, organically grown cold brew.
So we find ourselves at a school desk ordering from a concise lunch menu during a semi busy Saturday service. Oh, and it’s vegan bang in trend with most restaurants I went to in two weeks of grazing around Amsterdam.
Much like the decor, the food was a bit cobbled together and didn’t make much sense. Our oyster mushroom croquette with mustard greens over sourdough (it’s an open face sandwich) was less croquette and more suppli sized mushroom flavoured dough with a crust. It is a ‘croquette’ in the style of the local Dutch bitternballen which would work if it was the same size - the texture would make the dish better but not take it over the line. The open face sandwich proposition is pointless. This dish would be better conceptualised as a starter oyster mushroom bittenballen with a dip.
The cheesy padron pepper toastie is gooey and cheesy but doesn’t rise above the level of a home comfort sandwich regardless of the padron peppers.
Vegan food is a hard sell for many people and there are restaurants that are fighting to change paradigms and perceptions about vegan food making it exciting, winning hearts and minds.
This is not that place. There’s a lot here with a good location and the shabby chic is on trend but the core proposition of paying for food for enjoyment collapses.

name: De Ceuvel
Translated_Review:
Tucked away at the end of a cul-de-sac in the middle of a commercial zone. Formerly an abandoned shipyard, the site has been converted into a place to live and work. A group of enthusiasts struck a deal with the municipality, which in exchange for a 30-year lease entrusted them with the site, on condition that they return it completely cleaned up at the end of the lease.
Everything here has been built, assembled and imagined from recycled materials.
The bar, teeming with life both inside and out, the waterfront, with pontoons and floating terraces. Everywhere, refurbished and salvaged old houseboats have been placed on the polluted ground, and we move between them on raised walkways to make way for carefully selected plants that patiently carry out the work of decontamination. A host of companies have colonized these spaces, all involved in the arts or sciences related to ecology.
Another unclassifiable place where you can meet off the beaten track, with friends and/or strangers, around a log fire by the water, to the sound of a guitar or improvised bongos, or during a poetry or slam contest....
There's always something going on at De Ceuvel.

name: De Ceuvel
Translated_Review: It is not only a café, restaurant, concert terrace and recycling workshops. It is also an innovative project of a group of people who have created it from old and stranded boats, a meeting place. All based on a sustainable world, through solar energy, water purification and food and the use of plants. The cafeteria's prices are reasonable, with everything for vegetarians and carnivores. Very tasty cocktails and above all good opening hours and excellent service. Picnics are possible. I recommend an unmissable visit in Amsterdam.

name: De Ceuvel
Translated_Review: Pricey: yes. Worth it? YES! You spent your day in the city? Get out, go to Noord with the free ferry and let time pass and nature do its thing while you sip on delicious organic Kombucha! Also 100% worth to check out the good work people do in the boat-offices at De Ceuvel!

name: De Ceuvel
Translated_Review: I would love to say that this is an intentional community working in a sustainability-focused eco-village, but I'm not sure that would really tell the full story. The buildings are made from repurposed materials. The cafe strives for sustainability with all of their food. For example: the mushrooms and grown in coffee grounds discarded from other restaurants; and the only meat they serve is the geese that are hunted at schiphol airport to keep them from flying into plane engines. Yah, it's a cool place.

name: De Ceuvel
Translated_Review: This is a great place to hang out with friends for a bier or vegetarian food especially as part of a boat trip. Infact you can easily stop with the boat, chill and leave again. Prices are average. Coffee and espresso are not good so just slip them and go for drinks.

name: De Ceuvel
Translated_Review: An off the beaten track bar and terrace in the middle of dubious garages and forgotten companies. Their commitment to sustainability is praiseworthy and the decor is great. The only reason why I wouldn't give this place five stars is because in all their effort to be original their menu looks a lot like tons of other places in the hipster catalogue. Also, last time I was there the service was a bit too casual and slow. Therefore I would grade it 4 minus, if minuses where an option here. But definitely a place to check out if you haven't been yet!

name: De Ceuvel
Translated_Review:
Ate a noodle salad the other day topped with Vinegar. I thought it was gross and when asked if it tasted good, I replied it did not. Thereby missing the excess of different vegetables. Between the noodles were some shreds of leeks and a lot of super sour radishes.
The employee serving us looked up at that. It's an explosion of flavor, he said. And that sourness was exactly the point.
While paying, he mentioned that everyone at the Ceuvel thought it was a delicious salad. Next time I'd better go for the burger.
That next time, however, I doubt very much.

Ceuvel is like a raw diamond.
Think of it like a crowdfunded project that became a bar, a vegetarian restaurant, and a coworking space located on stranded houseboats. It has something magical to it, and a look reminiscent of the old bar25 in Berlin, without the crazy partying going on. Great for kids as they can jump in to the water, great to get to by boat, great to explore Noord from there.

name: De Ceuvel
Translated_Review: Amsterdam has a new hotspot for the summer, and it's in Noord, on the spot where De Ceuvel wharf used to be. De Ceuvel is entirely built with recycled materials and is nicely located on the water. The atmosphere is free-spirited. There is plenty of seating on the terrace and at the cafe itself. And if you want, you can swim there. The idea behind the Ceuvel is that in the future it will be completely self-supportive. That means that all the food - now still made with local products - will be grown in-house; and will remain affordable (because at EUR 12.50 for the main course it certainly is). For me, the taste of the food could be a bit more pronounced, but of course that is very personal. In any case, the atmosphere is very relaxed.

name: De Ceuvel
Translated_Review: Really awesome place to relax. Been there during the hot afternoon hours this summer and it was really great atmosphere. Cold beer, coffee, organic buffet, affordable prices and very kind stuff. There's plenty of space to sit, hang out or just jump in the water. Reminded me a little bit of the early days of bar25 in Berlin.
